Stu versions are of the form X.Y.Z, where X is the major version, Y is the minor version
and Z the patch level.

We followed Semantic Versioning rules:
* The major version X is increased when we make backward-incompatible changes.  This is
  rare.
* The major version Y is increased when a new feature is implemented.
* The patch version Z is increased for all other changes, including bugfixes, but also
  changes that are completely invisible in the released version (e.g., update text in
  doc/)

New features and major changes are documented in the file NEWS.  This includes only
changes which have their own tests under tests/[long-]<version>-<nnnn>.

The number zero (0) has special meaning for X/Y/Z in the version number:
* X=0:  Stu 0 was not subject to Semantic Versioning.
* Y=0:  These are pre-release versions.  They don't appear in the master branch.
* Z=0:  Not used.

Thus, the first release of a new major version is X.1.1, and the first release of a minor
version is X.Y.1.

When Z=1, we often omit the final ".1" in the version number.  E.g., version 2.17.1 can be
just called 2.17.  This convention is used in the names of testing directories under
tests/.

The versions given in NEWS for X=0 (stu 0.1, 0.2, etc.) do not reflect the history of
Stu.  These numbers have been created after the fact to allow tests under tests/ to have
names corresponding to features introduced at the time of Stu 0.
